            "answer_text": "The only well-written answers here are completely and utterly dead-wrong; thanks Quora, I was about to go to bed! The first Slavs (and the majority of Slavs today) belonged to haplogroup R1A; same as the ancient and modern Balts, and same as the ancient Thracians and Scythians. R1a-M458 is the largest of several exclusively Slavic subclades; being very rare in neighboring cousin Balts, but overwhelmingly common in Poles, Czechs, and the remains of most ancient Slavs from Lusatia to Serbia.   Today\u2019s Southern Slavs are descendants of a huge melting pot of ancient peoples; Serbia alone has more genetic diversity than almost all of Northern Europe! The primary haplogroup in the Balkans is I2, and it is indigenous there since at least 9,000 BC - one of the very oldest lineages in all of Europe. The first Slavs invaded the Balkans en masse between 380 - 620 AD, for which there are several historical accounts - prior to their arrival, the region was inhabited by Dacians and their Aromanian cousins, Illyrians (Albanians being their modern descendants), Greeks, hellenized Thracians, Romans, and even a small handful of very lost Goths. The only parts of the Balkans which even come close to having majority-descent from early Slavs today is Vojvodina in northern Serbia and neighboring Slavonia in Croatia, where just over half the population belongs to haplogroup R1a (compared to well over 80% in Poland, Slovakia, and Ukraine).  There is no one \u201cTurkic\u201d haplogroup; but most of Central Asia\u2019s speakers of Turkic languages belong to haplogroup C2, same as Mongolians and many Koreans and Japanese; with a few belonging to Q, which is near-nonexistent in Europe but common among Siberian tribes and Native Americans. The world\u2019s Turkic peoples have their earliest origins in far-western China and far-southwestern Mongolia, a region where C2 is the overwhelmingly dominant haplotype.  That all being said; these central Asian haplotypes are actually pretty damn rare in Europe. The only Slavs with significant admixture from C2 or Q are in Southern Ukraine (especially Crimea and Bessarabia), coastal Bulgaria, and southern Russia. Many Russians, especially, have rich and varied family trees from all over the former Russian Empire, including Central Asia. Many Ukrainians are descendants of the Cossacks, who often counted Turkic-speaking peoples (and even some Mongolic Kalmyks) among their ranks. Even so, no one region inhabited by Slavs has more than 5% Central Asian admixture; and in regions inhabited by the old Proto-Slavs (North-central and Eastern Poland, Belarus, Northwestern Ukraine) , that quantity of Central Asian haplotypes is near Zero. ",
